Price prediction for Airbnb listings in Toronto

Technical report

Created by Zsófia Rebeka Katona
Data Analysis 3
MS in Business Analytics
2023/2024 Winter term

Aim of the report: To show the technical aspects of the data set, including data cleaning, feature engineering, model selection and model visualization.

Project goal: To provide an overview on Airbnb price listings for a company, operating with accommodations to 2-6 guests. My recommendations for pricing and further views based on my findings can be found in the report.

About the dataset¶

  • The data set contains 20,386 Airbnb listings, spanning across various attributes including host details, property characteristics, pricing, availability, and guest reviews.
  • The data contains 238,342 missing values in total.
  • Features, like accommodates, beds, number_if_review, and review_scores_rating are expected to be significant predictors of the target variable.

Data source: Inside Airbnb

More information on the Airbnb listings in Toronto: Toronto Summary

Data cleaning¶

  • Data cleaning included dropping unneccessary columns, 16 in total out of 75, leaving 59 variables to work with.
  • I transformed the binary columns to booleans, turning t/f values to True or False.
  • I converted columns from object to datetime or percentages.
  • I cleaned the target variable, price column, transformed it to float type, dropped all NA values and renamed the column to usd_price_day.
  • I filtered for 2-6 number of guests.
  • I filtered for the property tpyes that correspond to small or mid-sized apartments and categorized them into Rental Unit or House for a more transparent comparison.
  • I renamed the room types.
  • As the bathrooms column had too many missing values, I decided to use the bathrooms_text predictor and manually convert the string information to numeric.
  • I pooled values where the results would have been to fragmented due to the large variety of values.
    • bathrooms: As we are talking about an apartment for 2-6 accommodates, it’s important to check if there is one or more bathrooms. Based on this, I created bins for apartments with 0, 1 and 2-10 bathrooms. I checked the number of reviews, where the mean was 27, and for simplicity and balance, I decided to bin the data according to that.
    • number_of_review
    • minimum_nights: Many travelers have preferences for staying for 1, 2, or 3 nights, especially for shorter trips or weekend getaways, hence I created bins according to that.
  • I handled missing values with 3 different approaches:
    • I dropped everything in the target variable.
    • In instances of few missing values, I performed imputation by substituting missing values with the median or, for grouped variables, assigning them to the most frequent category.
    • In cases where there was a significant number of missing values, and alternative data could be leveraged, such as substituting bedrooms with number of beds, I opted for the alternative data column.
    • Certain columns like calendar_updated and host_neighbourhood were excluded from analysis due to their lack of relevance or informative value. However, for important factors like neighborhood, a cleaned version was utilized.
    • Notably, for critical variables, particularly guest review metrics, missing values were flagged.
  • I transformed and renamed the columns with numerical variables, and renamed the categorical variables to oversee the data types easily.
  • It’s important to mention that the amenities column didn’t contain any valuable information, possibly because the data was scraped recently, on the 8th of January, 2024.

# When there is a few and not that important, we can impute them

    host_response_rate=lambda x: x["host_response_rate"].fillna(np.median(x["host_response_rate"].dropna())),
    host_acceptance_rate=lambda x: x["host_acceptance_rate"].fillna(np.median(x["host_acceptance_rate"].dropna())),
    d_host_is_superhost=lambda x: x["d_host_is_superhost"].fillna(0),
    bathrooms=lambda x: x["bathrooms"].fillna(np.median(x["bathrooms"].dropna())),
    beds=lambda x: np.where(x["beds"].isnull(), x["accommodates"], x["beds"]),
    minimum_nights=lambda x: x["minimum_nights"].fillna(1),
    number_of_reviews=lambda x: x["number_of_reviews"].fillna(1)
)

EDA¶

  • I have analyzed the price distributions and found that the 90th percentile is around USD 300 a day.
  • I opted to drop the higher values to examine the pricing patterns and characteristics of the more typical listings within the dataset, which are likely to be more representative of the general market trends.
  • Prices of houses and rental units exhibit similar ranges (from 50 to 175 USD), with the mean around USD 133.
  • The price distribution is a bit skewed to the right and right tail contains extreme values, they may make RMSE more sensitive.
  • As the 95th percentile included another USD 100, I decided to create another data set to compare to the results to it in the end of the analysis.

1. Model: OLS¶

Model 1. Regression of price on number of accommodates¶

$price=\beta_0 + \beta_1 accommodates$

  • Building the models incrementally, I started with regressing the price on the number of guests.
  • The R squared of the models increased gradually (from 0.183 to 0.391)
  • Comparing the first regression to the other models in stargazer, it became visible that room types have a greater impact on the target variable.
  • The comparison between OLS and Lowess uggested that the linear model could easily find a good fit.
  • Despite the high BIC values moving around 113000, the RMSE of the models ranged between 50 and 59, with Model 4 fitting the data best among all the four models (50.559).

def cv_reg(formula, data, kfold, testdata, robustse=None):
    regression_list = []
    predicts_on_test = []
    rsquared = []
    rmse_list = []
    rmse_list_test = []

    # Calculating OLS for each fold
    
    for train_index, test_index in k.split(data):
        data_train, data_test = data.iloc[train_index, :], data.iloc[test_index, :]
        if robustse is None:
            model = smf.ols(formula, data=data_train).fit()
        else:
            model = smf.ols(formula, data=data_train).fit(cov_type=robustse)
        regression_list += [model]
        predicts_on_test += [model.predict(data_test)]
        rsquared += [model.rsquared]

        rmse_tr = pd.concat(
            [data_train["usd_price_day"], model.predict(data_train)],
            axis=1,
            keys=["usd_price_day", "predicted"],
        )
        rmse_tr = rmse_tr[~rmse_tr.isna().any(axis=1)]

        rmse_te = pd.concat(
            [data_test["usd_price_day"], model.predict(data_test)],
            axis=1,
            keys=["usd_price_day", "predicted"],
        )
        rmse_te = rmse_te[~rmse_te.isna().any(axis=1)]

        rmse_list += [rmse(rmse_tr["usd_price_day"], rmse_tr["predicted"], axis=0)]
        rmse_list_test += [rmse(rmse_te["usd_price_day"], rmse_te["predicted"], axis=0)]
    nvars = model.df_model

    # We return a dictionary with the 
    return {
        "regressions": regression_list,
        "test_predict": predicts_on_test,
        "r2": rsquared,
        "rmse": rmse_list,
        "rmse_test": rmse_list_test,
        "nvars": nvars,
    }

# Summarize method --> gives us a df
def summarize_cv(cvlist, stat="rmse"):
    result = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Model" + str(x + 1): cvlist[x][stat] for x in range(len(cvlist))}
    )
    result["Resample"] = ["Fold" + str(x + 1) for x in range(len(cvlist[0]["rmse"]))]
    result = result.set_index("Resample")
    result = pd.concat([result, pd.DataFrame(result.mean(), columns=["Average"]).T])
    return result

Doing LASSO in another way to check out lambda values¶

  • Analyzing the lambda values separately, we can see that the stronger regularization causes the $R^2$ values to decrease for both the training and test sets.
  • Using the best lambda value (0.2), none of the coefficients were close to 0, suggesting that even the best lambda value might be too weak, allowing the coefficients to retain relatively higher values.
  • Comparing the actual prices to the predicted prices of Model 3 indicated that the model is underfitting up to $150, but above that price the model turns into overfitting.

3. Model: Random Forest¶

  • I set the train size to 0.7 and the random state to 42 as a standard.
  • The training set consisted of 7263 observations, meanwhile the hold out set contained 3113 observations.
  • I chose the most important accommodation characteristics as the basic_vars and grouped the reviews together.
  • Due to the fresh data, my amenities only consisted of dummies regarding the host.
  • The theoretical recommended number of variables was 12.61.
  • RandomForest gave a similar range of RMSE values, from 52 to 58.
  • According to the best estimator, the best performing tree obtains 12 predictors with the minimum of 5 observations in each node and has an RMSE value of 52.38.
  • Exploring the feature importance values showed me that the most important predictors are the private room type, the number of guests, the number of beds, the reviews per month and if there is a bathroom (1) in the apartment.

Final diagnostics¶

  • I compared the models' performance based on their RMSE values, which showed that the OLS has overperformed LASSO and RandomForest greatly.
  • There is still a noticable difference between the second best, RandomForest (52.39) and the weakest performing model (53.443).
  • Regressing the price on the variables with the highest feature importance yielded worse results than expected. Comparing the RMSE value of the most complex linear regression with variables selected by hand (50.559) and the last regression (54.705) shows us a significant difference.

# Comparing the first linear regression with reg5, the "optimal" regression model
sg = stargazer.Stargazer([reg1, reg5])

# Setting the covariate order
covariate_order = ["f_room_type[T.Private]", "f_room_type[T.Shared]",
                   "n_accommodates", "n_beds", "Intercept"]
sg.covariate_order(covariate_order)

sg.rename_covariates({"n_accommodates": "Accommodates", 
                      "f_room_type[T.Private]": "Private Room Type", 
                      "f_room_type[T.Shared]": "Shared Room Type", 
                      "n_beds" : "Beds",
                      "Intercept": "Constant"})

# Adding RMSE for measurement in the full sample for each model
rmse_values = [round(rmse(x.fittedvalues, data.usd_price_day), 3) for x in [reg1, reg5]]
sg.add_line('RMSE', rmse_values, location=stargazer.LineLocation.FOOTER_BOTTOM)

# Adding BIC for measurement in the full sample for each model
bic = [round(x.bic, 2) for x in [reg1, reg5]]
sg.add_line('BIC', bic, location=stargazer.LineLocation.FOOTER_BOTTOM)

Interestingly, regressing the price on the variables with the highest feature importance yielded worse results than expected. Comparing the RMSE value of the most complex linear regression (50.559) and this regression (54.705) shows us a significant difference. This indicates that while certain features may have high importance in RandomForest, their predictive power may not translate well to other types of models.

Truncating prices at the 90th percentile might not be ideal, as there are important values exceeding $300, suggesting that a broader range of prices could provide more accurate insights.
